some of the country’s most prominent social thinkers-among them Francis Fukuyama, Daniel Yankelovich, Amitai Etzioni, Alan Wolfe, Uwe Reinhardt, and Thomas E. Mann-reject the myth of polarization. On topics ranging from the war on terrorism, health care, economic policy, and Social Security to religion, diversity, and immigration, the authors argue that there are sensible, centrist solutions that are more in keeping with prevailing public sentiment and that would better serve the national interest. On issue after issue, the authors show how the conventional framing of the debate in Washington has misled Americans, creating a series of false dilemmas and forcing choices between two extremes-at the expense of more balanced and pragmatic policy solutions based on enduring American values.Uniting America provides a blueprint for a fresh approach to American politics, grounded in moderation, pragmatism, and the shared values that unite Americans.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDemocracyzUnited States. 0aPolarization (Social sciences). 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aSocial conflictzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aCheng, Tsung-mei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtzioni, Amitai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinn, Chester E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFukuyama, Francis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalston, William A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarfinkle, Norton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarfinkle, Norton, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMann, Thomas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarsh